 project of the Muslim intelligentsia that emerged in the Soviet context through the interstices of the complex politics of the period. Making Uzbekistan introduces key texts from this period and argues that what the decade witnessed was nothing short of a cultural revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSoviet & East European History.  aUzbekistan, USSR, imperial rule, colonialism, mass media, nationalism, state building.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170135140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701351/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles